# SQL Server Daily Health‑Check Guide

> **Audience:** SQL Server DBAs & system administrators
> **Frequency:** Recommended as a morning checklist (or via an automated Agent job)

---

## 1  Verify Long‑Running Transactions

| Why it matters | Long transactions keep locks open, prevent log truncation, and can balloon tempdb & transaction logs. |
| -------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |

### 1.1  Quick Snapshot (current session view)

```sql
SELECT
    s.session_id,
    s.login_name,
    at.transaction_id,
    at.transaction_begin_time,
    DATEDIFF(MINUTE, at.transaction_begin_time, GETDATE()) AS minutes_running,
    DB_NAME(dt.database_id)  AS database_name,
    dt.database_transaction_log_bytes_reserved/1024/1024 AS log_mb_reserved
FROM sys.dm_tran_active_transactions   at
JOIN sys.dm_tran_session_transactions st ON at.transaction_id = st.transaction_id
JOIN sys.dm_exec_sessions            s  ON st.session_id  = s.session_id
JOIN sys.dm_tran_database_transactions dt ON at.transaction_id = dt.transaction_id
WHERE at.transaction_type = 1         -- 1 = Read/Write
      AND DATEDIFF(MINUTE, at.transaction_begin_time, GETDATE()) > 5   -- threshold
ORDER BY minutes_running DESC;
```

### 1.2  Oldest Transaction Per Database

```sql
DBCC OPENTRAN;   -- Shows oldest open transaction in current DB
```

> **Tip:** Install [sp\_WhoIsActive](https://whoisactive.com) and run:

```sql
EXEC sp_WhoIsActive @get_transaction_info = 1, @find_block_leaders = 1;
```

### 1.3  Actions

1. Contact application owner if a batch legitimately needs time.
2. If it is idle (`status = sleeping`) but still holding locks, consider `KILL <spid>;`
3. Resize the log or run backup log if log reuse\_wait\_desc = `ACTIVE_TRANSACTION`.

---

## 2  Verify Technical (SQL Server Agent) Jobs

| What to check                 | How                                                                     |
| ----------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Last‑run outcome**          | Job Activity Monitor → "Last Run Outcome" column should be *Succeeded*. |
| **Failures in last 24 h**     | Query msdb.                                                             |
| **Disabled jobs / schedules** | Review monthly.                                                         |

### 2.1  Script: Failed jobs in last 24 h

```sql
;WITH LastRun AS (
    SELECT j.name, h.run_date, h.run_time,
           ROW_NUMBER() OVER(PARTITION BY j.job_id ORDER BY h.run_date DESC, h.run_time DESC) AS rn,
           h.run_status, h.message
    FROM msdb.dbo.sysjobs j
    JOIN msdb.dbo.sysjobhistory h ON j.job_id = h.job_id
    WHERE h.step_id = 0
      AND h.run_date >= CONVERT(INT, FORMAT(DATEADD(DAY,-1,GETDATE()),'yyyyMMdd'))
)
SELECT name, run_date, run_time, message
FROM   LastRun
WHERE  rn = 1 AND run_status <> 1;   -- 0 = Failed, 1 = Succeeded
```

### 2.2  Best Practices

* Enable **Database Mail** alerts for job failures (`sp_notify_job_owner`).
* Keep `msdb` history trimmed (`sysjobschedules`, `sp_purge_jobhistory`).

---

## 3  Verify Blocking / Concurrency Issues

### 3.1  Real‑Time Blocking Tree

```sql
;WITH Blk AS (
    SELECT  r.session_id, r.blocking_session_id, r.status, r.wait_type,
            r.wait_time/1000 AS wait_s, r.cpu_time/1000 AS cpu_s,
            SUBSTRING(st.text, r.statement_start_offset/2,
                      (CASE WHEN r.statement_end_offset = -1 THEN LEN(CONVERT(NVARCHAR(MAX), st.text)) * 2
                            ELSE r.statement_end_offset END - r.statement_start_offset)/2) AS stmt
    FROM sys.dm_exec_requests r
    CROSS APPLY sys.dm_exec_sql_text(r.sql_handle) st
    WHERE r.blocking_session_id <> 0
)
SELECT *
FROM Blk
ORDER BY wait_s DESC;
```

### 3.2  Actions

1. Locate **root blocker** (blocking\_session\_id that is *not* itself blocked).
2. Ask application team; if safe, `KILL <spid>`.
3. Capture deadlocks via extended events (`system_health`) for post‑mortem.

---

## 4  Check Table Volume & Growth

### 4.1  Top 20 Largest Tables in Current DB

```sql
SELECT TOP 20
    t.name      AS table_name,
    SUM(p.rows) AS row_count,
    SUM(a.total_pages) * 8/1024 AS total_mb,
    SUM(a.used_pages)  * 8/1024 AS used_mb
FROM sys.tables t
JOIN sys.indexes i          ON t.object_id = i.object_id
JOIN sys.partitions p       ON i.object_id = p.object_id AND i.index_id = p.index_id
JOIN sys.allocation_units a ON p.partition_id = a.container_id
GROUP BY t.name
ORDER BY total_mb DESC;
```

### 4.2  Other Useful Commands

* `EXEC sp_spaceused '[schema].[table]'` for a single object.
* `sp_MSforeachtable 'EXEC sp_spaceused "?"'` to loop (for quick estimates).
* Monitor file growth in `sys.master_files`.

---

## 5  Check CPU & Memory Utilization

### 5.1  Spot Check via DMV

```sql
-- CPU intensive sessions (last 5 min window)
SELECT TOP 5
    s.session_id,
    s.login_name,
    qs.total_worker_time/1000 AS cpu_ms,
    qs.execution_count,
    SUBSTRING(st.text, (qs.statement_start_offset/2)+1,
              ((CASE statement_end_offset WHEN -1 THEN DATALENGTH(st.text) ELSE qs.statement_end_offset END - qs.statement_start_offset)/2)+1) AS stmt
FROM sys.dm_exec_query_stats qs
CROSS APPLY sys.dm_exec_sql_text(qs.sql_handle) st
JOIN sys.dm_exec_sessions s ON qs.session_id = s.session_id
ORDER BY cpu_ms DESC;
```

### 5.2  Memory Pressure

```sql
SELECT
    (total_physical_memory_kb/1024) AS total_memory_mb,
    (available_physical_memory_kb/1024) AS available_memory_mb,
    system_memory_state_desc
FROM sys.dm_os_sys_memory;
```

> **Rule of Thumb:** Keep PLE (Page Life Expectancy) > 300 sec per 4 GB buffer.

### 5.3  OS‑Level Tools

* **perfmon** counters: `% Processor Time`, `Process(SQLSERVR)\% Processor Time`, `SQLServer:Buffer Manager\Page life expectancy`.
* **Task Manager** (CPU, RAM), **Resource Monitor**.

---

## 6  Check Disk Space & File Sizes

### 6.1  Free Space per Drive (SQL‑side)

```sql
EXEC master..xp_fixeddrives;
```

### 6.2  Database File Growth vs. Drive Capacity

```sql
SELECT
    DB_NAME(mf.database_id) AS database_name,
    mf.name                 AS logical_name,
    mf.type_desc,
    mf.size * 8/1024        AS size_mb,
    mf.max_size,
    vfs.available_bytes/1048576 AS free_mb_drive
FROM sys.master_files mf
CROSS APPLY sys.dm_os_volume_stats(mf.database_id, mf.file_id) vfs
ORDER BY free_mb_drive ASC;
```

### 6.3  Best Practices

* Keep at least **15–20 %** free on data drives; >20 % on log drives.
* Pre‑size data & log files, disable "auto‑grow by percent" for large DBs.
* Use **Volume Mount Points** for >26 drives.

---

## 7  Automation & Reporting

1. **One‑stop View:** Create a DBA database with tables for each metric and load via Agent job.
2. **Email Summary:** Use `sp_send_dbmail` to send HTML table results (set proper operator).
3. **PowerShell / dbatools:** `Get-DbaDiskSpace`, `Get-DbaSqlLogShipStatus`, etc.
4. **Dashboards:** Consider **SQL Monitor**, **SentryOne**, or custom Power BI with data from step 1.

---

## Appendix  – Quick Reference DMVs

| Area                | DMV / Command                                       |
| ------------------- | --------------------------------------------------- |
| Transactions        | `sys.dm_tran_active_transactions`, `DBCC OPENTRAN`  |
| Sessions & Requests | `sys.dm_exec_sessions`, `sys.dm_exec_requests`      |
| Blocking / Waits    | `sys.dm_os_waiting_tasks`, `sys.dm_os_wait_stats`   |
| CPU                 | `sys.dm_exec_query_stats`, `sys.dm_os_ring_buffers` |
| Memory              | `sys.dm_os_sys_memory`, `sys.dm_os_process_memory`  |
| Disk                | `sys.master_files`, `sys.dm_io_virtual_file_stats`  |
| Agent Jobs          | `msdb.dbo.sysjobs`, `msdb.dbo.sysjobhistory`        |

